⬆ 𝙈𝙖𝙮 "𝙙𝙞𝙫𝙤𝙧𝙘𝙚" 𝘬𝘢𝘺 𝘔𝘰𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘴 𝘯𝘰𝘰𝘯.

𝘗𝘦𝘳𝘰 𝙢𝙚𝙧𝙤𝙣 𝙥𝙖 𝙧𝙞𝙣 𝘬𝘢𝘺 𝙆𝙧𝙞𝙨𝙩𝙤.

𝘉𝘢𝘴𝘵𝘢 𝘢𝘯𝘨 𝙙𝙖𝙝𝙞𝙡𝙖𝙣 𝘯𝘨 "𝙙𝙞𝙫𝙤𝙧𝙘𝙚" 𝘢𝘺 𝙣𝙖𝙠𝙞𝙖𝙥𝙞𝙙 𝘰 𝙣𝙖𝙣𝙜𝙖𝙡𝙪𝙣𝙮𝙖 𝘢𝘯𝘨 𝙖𝙨𝙖𝙬𝙖. ⬇

text: Amor Conde pwedeng maging malaya kung abusado at inabandona na ang babae,   -meroon rin sa lalaki bigla nalang nawawala yung babae. Anullment isang legal na separation para kung may mga yaman ay hahatin nila, kung walang kakayahan na magbayad pwede naman maghiwalay kung ayaw na talaga, pero hindi ka mag aasawa sa iba, hindi makasal. Kaso nauso na ang pagli-live-in, which is hindi pahintulot ng simbahan na makasiping ka sa hindi mo asawa. Para hindi ka magkasala sa mata ng Diyos mas magandang hindi na mag aasawa at alagaan ang mga anak. Ang kaibahan sa divorce kasi pwede ka ikasal sa west hindi ka pwede sa simbahan Katoliko, magiging legal ang pagsasama dahil protektado sa batas ng devorce, Sa makataong batas, pero sa batas ng Diyos nakasala ka sa asawa mo.

text:
Marlon Tabuac 
 
𝖬𝖺𝗍𝖾𝗈 𝟣𝟫:𝟩-𝟫 (𝖳𝖫𝖠𝖡)

⁷ 𝖲𝗂𝗇𝖺𝖻𝗂 𝗇𝗂𝗅𝖺 𝗌𝖺 𝗄𝖺𝗇𝗂𝗒𝖺, 𝖡𝖺𝗄𝗂𝗍 𝗇𝗀𝖺 𝗶𝗽𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗴𝘂𝘁𝗼𝘀 𝗇𝗂 𝗠𝗼𝗶𝘀𝗲𝘀 𝗇𝖺 𝗺𝗮𝗴𝗯𝗶𝗴𝗮𝘆 𝗇𝗀 𝗸𝗮𝘀𝘂𝗹𝗮𝘁𝗮𝗻 𝗌𝖺 𝗽𝗮𝗴𝗵𝗶𝗵𝗶𝘄𝗮𝗹𝗮𝘆, 𝖺𝗍 𝗶𝗵𝗶𝘄𝗮𝗹𝗮𝘆 𝖺𝗇𝗀 𝖻𝖺𝖻𝖺𝖾? 

⁸ 𝖲𝗂𝗇𝖺𝖻𝗂 𝗇𝗂𝗒𝖺 𝗌𝖺 𝗄𝖺𝗇𝗂𝗅𝖺, 𝗗𝗮𝗵𝗶𝗹 𝗌𝖺 𝗸𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗴𝗮𝘀𝗮𝗻 𝗇𝗀 𝗂𝗇𝗒𝗈𝗇𝗀 𝗽𝘂𝘀𝗼 𝖺𝗒 𝗶𝗽𝗶𝗻𝗮𝘂𝗯𝗮𝘆𝗮 𝗌𝖺 𝗂𝗇𝗒𝗈 𝗇𝗂 𝗠𝗼𝗶𝘀𝗲𝘀 𝗇𝖺 𝗂𝗇𝗒𝗈𝗇𝗀 𝗵𝗶𝘄𝗮𝗹𝗮𝘆𝗮𝗻 𝖺𝗇𝗀 𝗂𝗇𝗒𝗈𝗇𝗀 𝗆𝗀𝖺 𝖺𝗌𝖺𝗐𝖺: 𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗮𝗽𝘂𝘄𝗮'𝘁 𝗯𝘂𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗌𝖺 𝗽𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗺𝘂𝗹𝗮 𝖺𝗒 𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗱𝗶 𝗴𝗮𝘆𝗼𝗻. 

⬆ 𝙈𝙖𝙮 "𝙙𝙞𝙫𝙤𝙧𝙘𝙚" 𝘬𝘢𝘺 𝘔𝘰𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘴 𝘯𝘰𝘰𝘯.

𝘗𝘦𝘳𝘰 𝙢𝙚𝙧𝙤𝙣 𝙥𝙖 𝙧𝙞𝙣 𝘬𝘢𝘺 𝙆𝙧𝙞𝙨𝙩𝙤.

𝘉𝘢𝘴𝘵𝘢 𝘢𝘯𝘨 𝙙𝙖𝙝𝙞𝙡𝙖𝙣 𝘯𝘨 "𝙙𝙞𝙫𝙤𝙧𝙘𝙚" 𝘢𝘺 𝙣𝙖𝙠𝙞𝙖𝙥𝙞𝙙 𝘰 𝙣𝙖𝙣𝙜𝙖𝙡𝙪𝙣𝙮𝙖 𝘢𝘯𝘨 𝙖𝙨𝙖𝙬𝙖. ⬇

⁹ 𝖠𝗍 𝗌𝗂𝗇𝖺𝗌𝖺𝖻𝗂 𝗄𝗈 𝗌𝖺 𝗂𝗇𝗒𝗈, 𝖲𝗂𝗇𝗈𝗆𝖺𝗇𝗀 𝗶𝗵𝗶𝘄𝗮𝗹𝗮𝘆 𝖺𝗇𝗀 𝗄𝖺𝗇𝗂𝗒𝖺𝗇𝗀 𝗮𝘀𝗮𝘄𝗮𝗻𝗴 𝖻𝖺𝖻𝖺𝖾, 𝗹𝗶𝗯𝗮𝗻 𝗇𝖺 𝗄𝗎𝗇𝗀 𝗌𝖺 𝗽𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗸𝗶𝗮𝗽𝗶𝗱, 𝖺𝗍 𝗆𝖺𝗀𝖺𝗌𝖺𝗐𝖺 𝗌𝖺 𝗂𝖻𝖺, 𝖺𝗒 𝗇𝖺𝗀𝗄𝖺𝗄𝖺𝗌𝖺𝗅𝖺 𝗇𝗀 𝗉𝖺𝗇𝗀𝖺𝗇𝗀𝖺𝗅𝗎𝗇𝗒𝖺: 𝖺𝗍 𝖺𝗇𝗀 𝗆𝖺𝗀𝖺𝗌𝖺𝗐𝖺 𝗌𝖺 𝖻𝖺𝖻𝖺𝗂𝗇𝗀 𝗒𝖺𝗈𝗇 𝗇𝖺 𝗁𝗂𝗇𝗂𝗐𝖺𝗅𝖺𝗒𝖺𝗇 𝖺𝗒 𝗇𝖺𝗀𝗄𝖺𝗄𝖺𝗌𝖺𝗅𝖺 𝗇𝗀 𝗉𝖺𝗇𝗀𝖺𝗇𝗀𝖺𝗅𝗎𝗇𝗒𝖺.

text:
Here are some additional negative consequences of divorce: 

Mental Health: Individuals who have gone through a divorce often experience feelings of unhappiness, increased stress, and other emotional issues. They may suffer from intense anxiety, depression, or other mental health problems, even many years after the divorce. 

Physical Health: Both men and women who have experienced divorce face higher rates of mortality, overall illness, and substance abuse compared to married individuals. In developed countries, divorced men and women have twice the premature mortality rate of married couples. They are also reportedly more susceptible to catching colds and flu. 

Financial Stability: Divorce can result in financial instability and the challenge of making independent financial decisions. Some individuals may find this newfound independence overwhelming, especially if they are used to a long-term partnership. 

Personal Growth: The emotional impact of divorce can impede personal growth, at least in the short term. In the early stages of divorce, most people feel overwhelmed and operate in “crisis mode”. 

Social Life: Some individuals may distance themselves from friendships and grapple with feelings of unhappiness after the divorce. These are just a few examples. The effects of divorce are complex and far-reaching, and while divorce may be unavoidable in some situations, it is important to acknowledge and address the potential consequences.

Sira na ang isang relasyon bago pa man magdesisyon ang mag-asawa na mag-divorce, depensa ni Albay 1st District Rep. Edcel Lagman sa divorce bill. 

Basahin ang ulat sa comment section.
text:
Edcel Lagman's assertion that "a relationship is already broken before a couple decides to divorce" reflects a fatalistic perspective that undermines the potential for reconciliation and healing within marriages. This viewpoint assumes an inevitable conclusion, disregarding the possibility of addressing issues and rebuilding the relationship through communication, therapy, and mutual effort. 

Lagman's reasoning falls into the fallacy of determinism, suggesting that the state of the marriage is predestined and beyond repair. This negates the dynamic and evolving nature of human relationships, where change and improvement are always possible. This stance disregards the principles of hope, personal growth, and the power of choice in altering one's circumstances.

In addition, this perspective conflicts with many religious teachings that emphasize the sanctity and resilience of marriage. Many faith traditions advocate for perseverance, forgiveness, and the transformative potential of love, even in the face of significant challenges. Lagman's view dismisses these values, promoting a defeatist attitude rather than encouraging couples to seek help and work towards resolution.

Moreover, Lagman's position is influenced by his own communist-leaning principles, which often prioritize state intervention over individual and familial autonomy. This approach can undermine the foundational societal unit of the family, which is essential for fostering stable and nurturing environments for both adults and children.

text:
Gospel
Mk 10:1-12
Jesus came into the district of Judea and across the Jordan.
Again crowds gathered around him and, as was his custom,
he again taught them.
The Pharisees approached him and asked,
"Is it lawful for a husband to divorce his wife?"
They were testing him.
He said to them in reply, "What did Moses command you?"
They replied,
"Moses permitted a husband to write a bill of divorce
and dismiss her."
But Jesus told them,
"Because of the hardness of your hearts
he wrote you this commandment.
But from the beginning of creation, God made them male and female.
For this reason a man shall leave his father and mother
and be joined to his wife,
and the two shall become one flesh.
So they are no longer two but one flesh.
Therefore what God has joined together,
no human being must separate."
In the house the disciples again questioned Jesus about this.
He said to them,
"Whoever divorces his wife and marries another
commits adultery against her;
and if she divorces her husband and marries another,
she commits adultery."

postTitle:
Sira na ang isang relasyon bago pa man magdesisyon ang mag-asawa na mag-divorce, depensa ni Albay 1st District Rep. Edcel Lagman sa divorce bill. 

Basahin ang ulat sa comment section.
text:
From a logical and practical perspective:

“It is erroneous to contend that by recognizing absolute divorce, we will be doing a great favor to the innocent spouse, especially the battered wife as it will enable her to get out of an unbearable marital relationship. 

On the contrary, it will be doing a greater favor to the guilty spouse, particularly the philandering and violent husband, because divorce enables him to get out of the marital relationship by committing acts that constitute grounds for absolute divorce and then remarry again and still continue to commit those acts every time he wants to get out of the marital relationship he has repeatedly entered into.” - J Sison, Manila Bulletin.

From a legal perspective:

Art. XV, set. 2, 1987 Constitution. "Marriage, as an inviolable social institution, is the foundation of the family and shall be protected by the State."

It is generally considered that marriage is a civil contract, at least in the sense that it is entered into by agreement of the parties. However, while marriage is a contract and purely civil, it is also and specially a status. 

“Marriage in this country is an institution in which the community is deeply interested. The state has surrounded it with safeguards to maintain its purity, continuity and permanence. The security and stability of the state are largely dependent upon it. It is the interest and duty of each and every member of the community to prevent the bringing about of a condition that would shake its foundation and ultimately lead to its destruction.” - Jimenez v. Republic.

“The basis of human society throughout the civilized world is that of marriage. The reason is that such is the common order of society, and if the parties were not what they thus hold themselves out as being, they would be living in the constant violation of decency and of law.” - Adong vs. Cheong Seng Gee.

From a socio-cultural perspective:

"One good reason why people still marry is that they still believe in their ability to decide and stand by that decision no matter what happens. They know that every choice involves the risk of being mistaken, yet they take the leap of faith. They do not wait until they are absolutely sure before choosing; rather, they choose first and then “make sure.” This means not only affirming that their decision is true and right but also exerting every effort to make the decision true and right for them. They understand that marriage is not a finished product but a lifetime endeavor they can accomplish together. 

They also believe that marriage is not just a contract where people exchange goods and services; it is a covenant wherein a couple gives themselves to each other. It is rooted in a more sublime covenant that God established between Himself and us from the very beginning. 

Many will think these are all pious platitudes difficult to apply to real-life situations. They are convinced that legalizing divorce will promote peace in the family and boost the household’s finances and the nation’s economy. However, a study by the Australian Institute of Family Studies showed that in many countries where divorce is legalized, there is a substantial negative effect on household incomes in the short term, with no evidence of recovery over the medium term." - Fr. Dela Rosa, OP

From a Religious-Theological perspective:

The Catholic Church teaches that marriage is a sacred covenant between a man and a woman, reflecting the union of Christ and His Church. According to the Catechism of the Catholic Church paragraph 2384, “divorce is a grave offense against the natural law because it breaks the contract to which the spouses freely consented, to live with each other until death.” 

Jesus Himself spoke against divorce, saying, “What therefore God has joined together, let not man put asunder.” However, the Church does recognize that in some cases, separation may be necessary, but this does not dissolve the marriage bond. In cases where a marriage is found to be invalid from the start, an annulment may be granted, which is a declaration that a valid marriage never existed. 

Marriage, according to Catholic teaching, has two primary purposes: the good of the spouses and the procreation and education of children. The Catechism of the Catholic Church, paragraph 1601 states, “The matrimonial covenant, by which a man and a woman establish between themselves a partnership of the whole of life, is by its nature ordered toward the good of the spouses and the procreation and education of offspring. Children are indeed a natural and essential part of marriage, but the mutual support and sanctification of the spouses are equally important.” No one has ever insisted that couples have to have children to be married. It is not that every marriage has a child, it is that every child has a mom and a dad. Marriage tries to maximize the likelihood that the child must be raised by parents. The public policy purpose of marriage is still being served by having that couple live out the truth about marriage.  

From an absolute divorce to “any types of marriage”:

“We can now address the arguments of those on the Left who think marriage is malleable to no end (call them “constructivists”). Marriage is for them whatever we decide to make it. 

Constructivism faces several problems, as we will show. First, it is often motivated by the fallacy, easy to dispel, that because social practices are partly constructed, they must be entirely constructed. Second, it can make no sense of major philosophical and legal traditions. Third, it also contradicts the spirit of common revisionist arguments, and would imply that many revisionists’ views are, by their own lights, as radically unjust as they consider ours to be. Finally, even if constructivism were true, it would provide no good basis for the revisionist view.” - Ryan Anderson. 

For better, for worse:

“It is the principle that all noble things have to be paid for, even if you only pay for them with a promise. The attack on marriage is an argument for celibacy. It is not an argument for divorce. For that entanglement which celibacy avowedly avoids, divorce merely reduplicates and repeats. There is a real sense in which free love might free men. But freer divorce would catch them in the most complicated net ever woven in this wicked world.

The tragedy of love is in love, not in marriage. There is no unhappy marriage that might not be an equally unhappy concubinage, or a far more unhappy seduction. Whether the tie be legal or no, matters something to the faithless party; it matters nothing to the faithful one. The pathos reposes upon the perfectly simple fact that if any one deliberately provokes either passions or affections, he is responsible for them as long as they go on, as the man is responsible for letting loose a flood or setting fire to a city. 

His escape is despair—which is called, in this connection, divorce. For every healthy man feels one fundamental fact in his soul. He feels that he must have a life, and not a series of lives.” - G.K. Chesterton.

To conclude, absoulte divorce is not the answer. So marriage is institutionalized as a sacrament because women were treated as property that could be disposed of. With absolute divorce, women are cheap again.

postTitle:
Sira na ang isang relasyon bago pa man magdesisyon ang mag-asawa na mag-divorce, depensa ni Albay 1st District Rep. Edcel Lagman sa divorce bill. 

Basahin ang ulat sa comment section.
text:
"The problem with an argument based on God is that it is the last resort of a bad debater," said Sen. Miriam Defensor Santiago, a supporter of the passage of a divorce law and a graduate of MA in Theology.

Ang Pilipinas ang nag-iisang bansa sa buong mundo, bukod sa Vatican, na walang batas ukol sa diborsyo. Kahit ang Espanya, ang bansa na nagpakilala ng Kristiyanismo sa Pilipinas, ay mayroong batas na nagpapahintulot sa diborsyo. Ang katotohanang ito ay nagbubukas ng maraming katanungan tungkol sa kung bakit nananatiling sarado ang ating bansa sa posibilidad ng diborsyo. Kung ang Espanya mismo, na malalim ang ugat sa Kristiyanismo, ay nakikita ang pangangailangan ng diborsyo, ito ba ay hindi sapat na indikasyon na ang diborsyo ay isang mahalagang batas para sa kapakanan ng mga mamamayan?

Source: https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/623308/philippines-and-the-vatican-are-the-only-countries-left-without-divorce/story/

2. Realidad ng Pang-Aabuso at Hindi Matibay na Relasyon:

Hindi lahat ng kasal ay nagtatapos sa pagmamahalan at pagkakaunawaan. Maraming mga tao ang nabubuhay sa mga relasyon na puno ng pang-aabuso, pisikal man o emosyonal. Ang hindi pagkakaroon ng opsyon sa diborsyo ay naglalagay sa mga biktima sa mas mahirap na sitwasyon, at tinatanggalan sila ng pagkakataong magsimula muli ng mas maayos at mas ligtas na buhay. Ayon sa mga pag-aaral, ang mga biktima ng domestic violence ay madalas na walang magawa dahil sa kawalan ng legal na paraan upang makalaya mula sa kanilang mga abuser.

Source: https://www.pids.gov.ph/publication/discussion-papers/domestic-violence-in-the-philippines-an-overview-of-government-initiatives-and-programs

3. Pagkakapantay-pantay at Karapatang Pantao:

Ang diborsyo ay hindi lamang isang isyu ng relihiyon o kultura, kundi ito rin ay isang usapin ng karapatang pantao. Ang pagkakaroon ng kalayaan upang makalaya mula sa isang hindi maganda at mapanganib na relasyon ay isang karapatang pantao na dapat iginagalang at pinoprotektahan ng batas. Ang pagtataguyod ng karapatang ito ay magbibigay daan para sa mas makatao at makatarungang lipunan.

Source: https://hrw.org/news/2020/07/16/philippines-criminalizing-women-fighting-their-rights

4. Ang Papel ng Simbahan at Estado:

Mahalaga ang papel ng relihiyon sa ating kultura, subalit kailangan nating kilalanin ang hiwalay na papel ng estado sa pagbibigay ng proteksyon at serbisyo sa lahat ng mamamayan. Ang batas ay dapat na para sa lahat, hindi lamang sa mga naniniwala sa isang partikular na pananampalataya. Ang estado ay may tungkulin na siguraduhin na ang lahat ng mamamayan ay may pantay-pantay na proteksyon at pagkakataon na mamuhay nang masaya at ligtas.

Source: https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2018/09/10/divorce-church-separation.html

5. Mga Aral mula sa Ibang Bansa:

Maraming bansa, kahit na ang mga may matibay na ugat sa relihiyon, ang may mga batas na nagpapahintulot sa diborsyo. Ang mga bansang ito ay nakahanap ng balanse sa pagitan ng pagpapahalaga sa institusyon ng kasal at sa pagbibigay ng proteksyon at opsyon para sa mga indibidwal na nasa mapanganib at hindi na maligaya na relasyon. Ayon sa isang pag-aaral ng Pew Research Center, ang mga bansang may divorce laws ay nagpapakita ng mas mataas na antas ng kaligayahan at kasiyahan sa buhay ng mga mamamayan.

Source: https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2019/04/22/how-marriage-age-and-divorce-impact-marriage-rates-across-religions/

https://www.pewresearch.org/religious-landscape-study/database/marital-status/

6. No Divorce is Anti-Poor and Pro-Oppressor:
Ang hindi pagkakaroon ng diborsyo ay isang anyo ng pangaapi, lalo na sa mga mahihirap na walang kakayahang makuha ang mahal at komplikadong proseso ng annulment. Ang sistemang ito ay pumapabor sa mga nasa kapangyarihan at may kaya, habang ipinagkakait ang hustisya sa mga inaapi at walang kakayahan. Ang kawalan ng diborsyo ay naglalagay ng mas malaking pasanin sa mga mahihirap, na kadalasang walang paraan upang makatakas sa mapang-abusong relasyon.

Dito pumapasok ang konsepto ng Liberation Theology, isang kilusang teolohikal na binibigyang diin ang paglaya ng mga inaapi at mahihirap mula sa kanilang mga kalagayan. Naniniwala ang Liberation Theology na tungkulin ng simbahan at ng lipunan na tulungan ang mga taong nangangailangan ng katarungan at kalayaan. Ang pagpasa ng diborsyo ay isang hakbang sa pagtulong sa mga taong nagdurusa sa hindi maligaya at mapang-abusong relasyon. Ito ay isang pagkilala na ang bawat tao, anuman ang kanilang kalagayan, ay may karapatang mabuhay ng may dignidad at kalayaan mula sa pang-aabuso.

Source: https://www.britannica.com/topic/liberation-theology
Bakit Hindi Sapat ang Legal Separation at Annulment:

1. Legal Separation:

Ang legal separation ay hindi nagbibigay ng karapatan sa muling pagpapakasal dahil hindi nito binubuwag ang kasal. Ang mga mag-asawang legal na naghiwalay ay mananatiling kasal sa mata ng batas, kaya’t limitado pa rin ang kanilang kalayaan na magsimula ng bagong relasyon na may legal na basbas.

2. Annulment:

Ang annulment naman ay isang komplikado at mahal na proseso na nagrerequire ng patunay na ang kasal ay invalid mula sa simula. Maraming tao ang hindi kayang bayaran ang gastos ng annulment, at marami rin ang hindi makahanap ng sapat na dahilan upang makakuha nito, lalo na kung walang malinaw na batayan sa ilalim ng batas.

Source: https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2017/09/05/1736301/expensive-elongated-process-annulment-philippines

Pagkilala at Paglaban para sa Karapatan:

Ang diborsyo ay isang hakbang tungo sa pagbibigay ng mas malawak na proteksyon at kalayaan sa bawat Pilipino. Ang pagkakaroon ng diborsyo ay magbibigay daan upang masigurado na ang bawat isa ay may pagkakataong mabuhay ng maligaya, ligtas, at may dignidad. Ang pagkakaroon ng diborsyo ay isang pagkilala na hindi lahat ng kasal ay perpekto, at ito ay isang pagpupugay sa karapatang pantao na maging malaya at masaya. Ipaglaban natin ang karapatan ng bawat isa na mamuhay ng walang takot at pang-aabuso.

text:
#yestodivorce
#freeUs
#Divorcepilipinas
#Divorcelawnow
#Reinstitutedivorce

I observed a very common misconception in the society. The idea that divorce will be an "easy" way out for people to commit adultery. Garbage rhetoric. The Divorce Bill has grounds listed that are specifically fit for our current society and more importantly, proper procedures and steps must be complied with. There is no such thing as a "file now, get results tomorrow" kind of process. Seriously. The people must be educated in the proper legal court proceedings.

Moreso, for concerns regarding the welfare of the children affected, parenting never stops even though the parents decide to go their separate ways. There are rehabilitative methods out there to help children cope with the transition in family dynamics. Yes, it is a sensitive time for them, but look at the bigger picture. Do you want a child to be raised in a toxic home full of parent's resentment of each other? Kids these days are smarter than you think. They can pick up and assess their situations more perceptively. Based on the opinions of the younger generation, they rather be far from all the toxicity than endure their parent's hostility. 

Everyone is entitled to their own opinions in regards to religious beliefs BUT at the same time, everyone has civil rights as an integral component of democracy. Meaning equal social opportunities and protection under law, regardless of race, social status and most importantly, religion. We all have a right to vote, to a fair trial, to avail government services, to a public education, to avail marriage AND TO DIVORCE. Everyone leads different lives and circumstances. Don't deprive our civil right to divorce a dead marriage just because of what you personally believe in.
